description:
Bug 38131ajc needs -d . I am using 1.1rc1. This is a regression since rc1 and a deviation from javac. I am guessing this may have something to do with a change in the underlying Eclipse compiler.

To reproduce the issue:
1. Create a class in a subpackage, for example:
   package subpackage;

   public class Test {
       public static void main(String[] args) {
           System.out.println("Hello");
       }
   }
2. Compile using the following command: ajc subpackage\Test.java

Observed Behavior:
After running the command, a directory named "subpackage" is created under the existing "subpackage" directory. The compiled file, test.class, is placed in the wrong location, causing the following error when trying to run the program:
Exception in thread "main" java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: subpackage/Test

Expected Behavior:
The compiled file should be placed in the correct location, allowing the program to run without errors.

Steps to Reproduce:
Run the following command: ajc -d . subpackage\Test.java

This workaround should resolve the issue.

Note: The behavior of the ajc command should be consistent with the javac command.
